AKURE – No fewer than 25 women were on Thursday honoured and enlisted in the Ondo State Female Hall of Fame by the state government for their out­standing contributions to the develop­ment of the state in the various areas of endeavour. Among the awardees were the first female Head of Service in the state, Mrs. Kosemani Kolawole, first female Speaker of the state House of Assembly, Jumoke Akindele and Dr.(Mrs.) Funmi­lola Williams-Daudu, a medical doctor, who carries out annual free medical services to the people of Akoko. According to the organiser, over 31,000 persons had benefited from the health programme organised by the awardee since it started. APC: Members Plan Heroic Welcome For CECPC Buni IWD: SWAN Urges NASS To Revisit Gender Bills Dr. Williams-Daudu was honoured and enlisted in the Female Hall of Fame for training midwives free and providing scholarship awards to indi­gent students and hiring and paying teachers for public schools in Ikaram- Akoko. She’s also into integrated farming where people are trained in different areas of farming with the aim of en­suring food security in the state. Commenting on the award, Dr. Wil­liams-Daudu described the award as an encouragement to do more.